Abstract

The analysis conducted aims to represent the level of satisfaction of young Italian graduates on an economic and social level, on the hypothesis that this may be to some extent associated with the brain drain phenomenon.

Introduction

The phenomenon known as brain drain is a very sensitive and central issue in the socio-political discussion in Italy. It refers to a countrys loss of skilled human capital and the simultaneous lack of brain circulation. As Alessandro Rosina, Professor of Demography and Social Statistics of the Catholic University of Milan explains, the phenomenon is entirely consistent with the development processes of this century. If on one hand there is the possibility of traveling with limited times and costs, on the other the attitude of the new generations has also changed, increasingly globalized, more inclined to move, to interact and deal with different cultures and realities. As the scholar points out, It is wrong to try to cage ones talents. On the other hand, however, even one-way flight is not desirable, because it impoverishes the place of departure. Using the words of E. Durkheim, we could to define the phenomenon as a social fact 1 characteristic of this century; the problem in Italy is the unidirectional process of the phenomenon in question: The optimal condition is instead circulation, that is, the possibility of being able to go, but with the same ease being able to do the reverse path and return. The problem of Italy are not the valuable many who leave, but the few who go the opposite way. This impoverishes our country and causes it to enter a negative spiral. 2 Italy, therefore, is facing a double challenge: on one hand, the worrying increase in the level of qualification of the human capital leaving the country (high-school and graduates) with consequent damage to national competitiveness. On the other hand, there is Italys scarce ability to attract skilled human capital from the rest of the world.

Chapter 1

1.1 Objective definition : social and economic analysis of young Italian graduates satisfaction

On the basis of the socio-demographic context described in the introduction of this article, the investigation illustrates the level of economic and social satisfaction of young Italian graduates between 20 and 34 years old, on the hypothesis that this may, to some extent, be associated with the brain drain phenomenon. The data considered are taken from the Multipurpose Survey on Families: Aspects of Daily Life. This is a sample survey proposed by ISTAT (starting from 1993 and carried out every year) aimed at detecting fundamental information relating to the daily life of individuals and families. The information collected describe the habits of citizens and the problems they face every day and whether they are satisfied with the functioning of those public utility services that should contribute to improving the quality of life. In the case in question, the data refer to the year 2018 and the variables relating to the satisfaction of ones economic and social life are taken into consideration. The proposed analysis, therefore, aims to study the profile of young Italian graduates (by region) on the basis of their level of satisfaction in respect to their economic and social sustainability.

1.2 Dataframe definition in accordance with the study objective

The giov variable reduces the size of the observations of the dataset AVQ_Microdati_2018 to young Italian high-school diploma and graduates aged between 20-34 years old, also filtering the main active variables considered for this project (aspects of economic satisfaction 317,689,690 and aspects of social satisfaction 319,320,321,453). The variables giov_laur_ita and giov_dipl_ita are also defined as young graduates (the first) and young high-school diploma (the second), useful for analyzes to compare the level of economic and social satisfaction between graduates and high-school diploma. The analysis conducted in the first surveys (monovariate and bivariate) aims at comparing the economic and social situation divided between graduates and high-school diploma, to have a comparison of the trend between the two categories. Lastly, the study is carried on only with the category of graduates, to illustrate the level of satisfaction proposed by the analysis objective. Following the surveys on young emigrants (eg. Il Fatto Quotidiano 3), there are more graduates than high-school diploma to leave the country; this comparison, therefore, could return interesting data on the trend of one or the other category.

# Define young italian graduates (also with diploma)
giov<- AVQ_Microdati_2018[AVQ_Microdati_2018$REGMF >= 10 &
                                     AVQ_Microdati_2018$REGMF <= 200 &
                                     AVQ_Microdati_2018$ETAMi >= 8 &
                                     AVQ_Microdati_2018$ETAMi <= 9 &
                                     AVQ_Microdati_2018$ISTRMi >= 1 &
                                     AVQ_Microdati_2018$ISTRMi <= 7 &
                                     AVQ_Microdati_2018$CITTMi == 1 
                                   ,c(6,7,11,20,21,317,689:690,319:321,453)]

# Transform variables in factors
for (i in 1:length(giov))
  giov[[i]]<-as.factor(giov[[i]])

# Label all illustrative variables
levels(giov$ETAMi) <-c("20-24", "25-34")
levels(giov$SESSO) <-c("male", "female")
levels(giov$ISTRMi) <-c("graduates","diploma")
levels(giov$REGMF) <-c("piemonte","valleAosta","lombardia","trentino",
                                "veneto","friuli","liguria","emiliaRomagna","toscana",
                                "umbria","marche","lazio","abruzzo","molise","campania",
                                "puglia","basilicata","calabria","sicilia","sardegna")
levels(giov$RIPMF)<-c("north-west","north-east","center", "south", "islands",
                               "not avail")

# Label all active variables
levels(giov$SITEC)<-c("very", "enough", "little", "not at all")
giov$SITEC<-factor(giov$SITEC, order=TRUE,
                            levels=c("not at all", "little", "enough", "very" ))
levels(giov$SITE)<-c("very improved", "little better",
                               "almost unchanged", "little worse", "much worse" )
giov$SITE<-factor(giov$SITE, order=TRUE,
                           levels=c("much worse", "little worse",
                                     "almost unchanged", "little better",
                                     "very improved" ))
levels(giov$RISEC)<-c("excellent", "adequate", "poor", "absolutely insufficient" )
giov$RISEC<-factor(giov$RISEC, order=TRUE,
                            levels=c("absolutely insufficient", "scarce",
                                      "adequate", "excellent" ))
levels(giov$RELFAM)<-c("very", "enough", "little", "not at all" )
giov$RELFAM<-factor(giov$RELFAM, order=TRUE,
                            levels=c("not at all", "little", "enough", "a lot"))
levels(giov$RELAM)<-c("very", "enough", "little", "not at all" )
giov$RELAM<-factor(giov$RELAM, order=TRUE,
                            levels=c("not at all", "a little", "enough", "a lot" ))
levels(giov$TEMLIB)<-c("very", "enough", "little", "not at all" )
giov$TEMLIB<-factor(giov$TEMLIB, order=TRUE,
                            levels=c("not at all", "a little", "enough", "a lot" ))
levels(giov$FUTUASP)<-c("it will improve", "it will stay the same", "it will get worse", "I don't know" )
giov$FUTUASP<-factor(giov$FUTUASP, order=TRUE,
                            levels=c("I don't know", "it will get worse",
                                      "will remain the same", "will improve" ))
# Define young graduates (diplomati)
giov_dipl_ita <- giov[giov$ISTRMi != "graduate",1:12]
# Define young graduates (laureati)
giov_laur_ita <- giov[giov$ISTRMi != "diploma",1:12]

In relation to the 2018 sample survey proposed by ISTAT, the new dataset is made up of 5012 young people aged 20-34, of which 1538 graduates and 3474 with high-school diploma. Among the variables, 5 illustrative variables were considered (in order age, sex, education, region of residence, geographical location) and 7 active variables, divided into 3 for the category economic satisfaction (in order Satisfaction with the economic situation in the last 12 months, Evaluation of the economic situation of the family compared to that of a year ago, Overall economic resources of the family in the last 12 months) and 4 for the category social satisfaction (in order Satisfaction with family relationships in the last 12 months, Satisfaction with relationships with friends in the last 12 months, Leisure time satisfaction in the last 12 months, Personal situation expectation in the next 5 years)

Chapter 3: Bivariate analysis

In this section will be illustrated the main bivariate analysis. To simplify the representation according to the analysis objective, the dataset has been resized by categorizing the active variables through (mainly) two levels: very satisfied and quite satisfied are categorized into satisfied , while the not satisfied and not satisfied at all become dissatisfied. The variable SITE (Evaluation of the economic situation of the family compared to that of a year ago) has been categorized into 3 levels: from much improved, little improved, almost unchanged, little worse and much worse a satisfied, average satisfied, dissatisfied. Finally, the variable FUTUASP (Expectation of personal situation in the next 5 years) remained unchanged.

3.1 Bivariate analysis

Starting from the giov_categ dataset and assuming that there might be a link between the variables of the different macro-areas, the bivariate analysis were carried out in particular between: satisfaction with economic sustainability, satisfaction with social sustainability and socio-demographic data. The analysis in question was performed by proceeding through the following phases:

  1. In the first phase it was calculated and printed the empirical and theoretical contingency tables on the screen in order to allow the immediate verification of the independence between the variables under study. Furthermore, the empirical table was plotted by means of a bubbleplot or fourfold.

  2. Subsequently it is proceeded to the calculation of the chi-square, which allowed us to verify the independence between the variables when the value of the same is equal to 0. The positive value of the index indicates, instead, a dependence between the two variables compared; dependence (degree of association between variables) which cannot be quantified, as the value of the index is influenced by the sample size. For this reason it was considered appropriate to proceed with the calculation of the Cramer index, which being normalized and purified from the sample size, allows to quantify the degree of association between the variables under study, with a value that varies between 0 and 1 ( V = 0 perfect independence, V = 1 perfect dependence).

  3. Finally, in order to analyze between which modalities of the two variables there is a dependence, we resorted to visualization through the mosaicplot, the latter, which has the function of automatically carrying out a statistical test, has allowed us to verify what degree of association exists between the different modalities of the variables under study.

  4. The most significant results obtained from the bivariate analysis were analyzed in detail by comparing the levels of economic and social satisfaction individually for young graduates and youngsters with high-school diploma.

a) bivariate analysis: satisfaction with economic sustainability and satisfaction with social sustainability

i) association between economic satisfaction in the last 12 months and satisfaction with family relationships in the last 12 months

Contingency tables, the Chi-square test and Cramers index show that there is a significant (medium-low) statistical association between economic satisfaction and satisfaction with family relationships of the young people under study (both variables refer to the satisfaction perceived in the last 12 months). The confirmation of the correctness of the analysis derives from the mosaicplot which for the category of qualified young people (graduates and diploma) shows a degree of positive association between economic dissatisfaction and dissatisfaction with family relationships and a negative association between dissatisfaction with family relationships and financial satisfaction. From the area of the two rectangles shown in the figure it is clear that there is a prevalence of young people who are dissatisfied both economically and in family relationships. Subsequently, we compared the mosaic plots obtained by considering, respectively, the young graduates category and the youngsters with high-school diploma category and as can be seen from the graphs as well as from the univariate analysis carried out previously, in young graduates the degree of economic and family relations dissatisfaction is a little more marked than that of young graduates.

Contingency tables, the Chi-square test, and Cramers index show that there is an not-significant statistical association between family economic satisfaction assessed with respect to the previous year and satisfaction with family relationships assessed in the last 12 months. The dependence between the two variables is confirmed by an empirical Chi-square value equal to 6.642 higher than the theoretical Chi-square equal to 5.991. The Cramer index gives an indication of the degree of association between the two variables under study which can be considered low (not very significant), as it is close to zero. The confirmation of the accuracy of the analysis carried out derives from the mosaic plot which for the category of qualified young people (graduates and with diploma) shows a low degree of positive association between dissatisfaction with family relationships and dissatisfaction with the family economic situation compared with last year.

Chapter 3: Multivariate analysis

In this section we will analyze the active variables under study, through the method of multiple correspondence analysis. The objective, therefore, is to analyze the relationships existing between the set of variables concerning the category economic satisfaction (SITEC, SITE and RISEC) and the category social satisfaction (RELFAM, RELAM, TEMLIB, FUTUASP) observed in the collective.

The analysis of the multiple correspondences illustrates how there is a strong association between the satisfied of the social category with the economic one. However, there is no association between those who are dissatisfied with their economic situation and those who are dissatisfied with the social dimension.

Conclusions

The investigations results show correspondence with the latest ISTAT studies regarding the number of Italians who emigrated abroad and reported by national newspapers. According to the article in Il Sole 24 Ore, in relation to the resident youth population, in the last ten years about 20 young people per 1,000 residents, of the same age group, have left Italy, with peaks in Trentino Alto Adige and Friuli Venezia Giulia [^ note4]. The analysis proposed in this project revealed a certain degree of dissatisfaction among young graduates (as highlighted by the interactive cartography on the right); In Northern Italy the degree of economic dissatisfaction is marked in Piemonte and Trentino Alto Adige, while in the South the degree of social dissatisfaction is prevalent with the highest rate in Campania. In conclusion, we observed that the data analysis lead us to evaluate the trend already highlighted by other national newspapers, according to which the degree of dissatisfaction (mainly economic) of the highly qualified youth population in Italy can be associated with the phenomenon of brain drain.
